{{Infobox Jewish leader | honorific-prefix = | name = Aaron Abiob | honorific-suffix = | title = | image = | caption = | synagogue = | synagogueposition = | yeshiva = | yeshivaposition = | organisation = | organisationposition = | began = | ended = | predecessor = | successor = | rabbi = | rebbe = | kohan = | hazzan = | rank = | other_post = <!---------- Personal details ----------> | birth_name = | birth_date = 1535 | birth_place = | death_date = {{death year and age |1605|1535}} | death_place = | yahrtzeit = | buried = | nationality = | denomination = | residence = | dynasty = | parents = | father = | mother = | spouse = | children = | occupation = | profession = | alma_mater = | semicha = | signature = }} '''Aaron Abiob''' ({{lang-he|אהרן אביוב}}) (1535–1605) was [[Turkic peoples|Turkish]]<ref>D. Rottenberg [https://books.google.com/books?id=IlL6kbumlKoC&pg=PA150 ''Finding our fathers'': a guidebook to Jewish genealogy ] Retrieved 2011-09-16.</ref> [[rabbi]]<ref>A. M. Hyamson [https://books.google.com/books?id=9y8LrtmeJwcC&pg=PA1 A Dictionary of Universal Biography: Of All Ages and of All Peoples] Retrieved 2011-09-16.</ref> of [[Salonica]].<ref name="mcn">{{cite book |title=Salonica |url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=http://www.mcnbiografias.com/app-bio/do/show%3Fkey%3Daaron-abiob&ei=fRpzTqrYCY26hAfknZW3DA&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEcQ7gEwBjgU&prev=/search%3Fq%3Daaron%2Babiob%26start%3D20%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DN%26biw%3D1034%26bih%3D751%26prmd%3Dimvnsb |publisher=mcnbiografias.com |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref> He was the author of ''Oil of Myrrh'', in the [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] known as Shemen ha-Mor (''ex ravvinorum{{Not a typo}} Myrrhoe commentariis Oleum''<ref name="mcn"/>), and was commentary on the [[Book of Esther]]. He lived and flourished in Salonica about 1540' his work being first printed in 1601,<ref>[http://studylight.org/enc/tje/view.cgi?n=324 The 1901 Jewish Encyclopedia] Retrieved 2011-09-16.</ref> and living for some time in [[Constantinople]].<ref>Marc Eliany [http://virtualpublications.ca/html/creationprofiles/themeaningofnames/a/aba.html virtualpublications] Retrieved 2011-09-16.</ref>
The name Aaron was given to the brother of Moses a person documented within the [[Torah]], this biblical Aaron was the founder of the priesthood.<ref>[http://www.jewfaq.org/search.htm?Keywords=Aaron Judaism 101] Retrieved 2011-09-16.</ref>
