{{Infobox saint |name=Abundius and Abundantius |birth_date= |death_date=c. 304 |feast_day=16 September |venerated_in= |birth_place= |death_place=north of Rome |titles= |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= }}
{{see also|Abundantius}} {{see also|Abundius (disambiguation)}}
'''Abundius and Abundantius''' (died c. 304) are [[Christian]] [[martyr]]s who were killed during the [[Diocletian persecution]]. Their [[feast day]] is celebrated on September 16.
==Biography== Abundius was a [[priest]] who had earlier [[resurrect]]ed [[John and Marcianus|'''John''', the son of '''Marcianus''']]. Upon hearing of this, the emperor ordered these three, with Abundantius, a deacon, to be [[decapitation|beheaded]]. The executions were carried out at the 26th [[milestone]] of the [[Via Flaminia]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Saint Augustine's Abbey|first=|date=30 June 2015 |title=The Book of Saints|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=hpfmCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=ru&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=|publisher=Aeterna Press|location=London, United Kingdom}}</ref>
==Veneration== Their bodies were later transferred to the church of [[Cosmas and Damian]] in Rome. The bodies of [[John and Marcianus|Marcianus and John]] were found around 1001 and transferred to [[Civita Castellana]]. There, they were elected to be the city's principal [[patron saints]]. In 1583, the relics of Abundius and Abundantius were transferred to the SS. Nome di Gesu, where they were placed under the church's [[altar|high altar]]. [[Aloysius Gonzaga]] heard [[mass]] there before becoming a [[Jesuit]].
==See also== *[[Abundius of Umbria]] – martyed north of Rome in the Diocletian persecution.<!-- are we sure they are different people in fact? --> *[[Abundius of Palestrina]]
