===Race and sexual orientation===
{{See also|Suicide among LGBT youth|Homosexuality and psychology}}

In 2003, in the United States, whites and Asians were nearly 2.5 times more likely to kill themselves than were blacks or Hispanics.<ref>{{cite journal| last1 = Hoyert
| first1 = Donna| first2= Melonie P. |last2=Heron |first3=Sherry L. |last3=Murphy |first4=Hsiang-Ching |last4=Kung | title = Deaths: Final Data for 2003| journal = National Vital Statistics Report| volume = 54| issue = 13| publisher = U.S. Department of Health and Human Services| date = 2006-04-19| url = https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr54/nvsr54_13.pdf| accessdate = 2006-07-22 |format=PDF}}</ref> There is a marked divergence by age as seen in the chart below.  In the eastern portion of the world (primarily in Asian or Pacific-Island countries) the numbers of reported suicides is growing every year.<ref>{{citation
 | title=Epidemiology of Suicide
 | publisher=Marten Publications
 | year=2008
 | work=Behind Asia's Epidemic
}}</ref>

The likelihood of suicide attempts are increased in both gay males and lesbians, as well as bisexuals of both sexes when compared to their heterosexual counterparts.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1300/J035v15n03_06 |title=Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual College Students |year=2001 |last1=Westefeld |first1=John |first2=Michael |first3=Brian |first4=Steve |journal=Journal of College Student Psychotherapy |volume=15 |pages=71–82 |last2=Maples |last3=Buford |last4=Taylor |issue=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fergusson DM, Horwood LJ, Ridder EM, Beautrais AL |title=Sexual orientation and mental health in a birth cohort of young adults |journal=Psychological Medicine |volume=35 |issue=7 |pages=971–81 |date=July 2005 |pmid=16045064 |doi=10.1017/S0033291704004222}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Silenzio VM, Pena JB, Duberstein PR, Cerel J, Knox KL |title=Sexual Orientation and Risk Factors for Suicidal Ideation and Suicide Attempts Among Adolescents and Young Adults |journal=American Journal of Public Health |volume=97 |issue=11 |pages=2017–9 |date=November 2007 |pmid=17901445 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2006.095943 |pmc=2040383}}</ref> The [[Gender and suicide|trend of having a higher incident rate]] among females is no exception with lesbians or bisexual females and when compared with homosexual males, lesbians are more likely to attempt than gay or bisexual males.<ref>[https://www.ucalgary.ca/~ramsay/attempted-suicide-gay-lesbian-all-studies.htm Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual & Transgender "Attempted Suicide" Incidences/Risks Suicidality Studies From 1970 to 2009]</ref>

Studies vary with just how increased the risk is compared to heterosexuals with a low of 0.8-1.1 times more likely for females<ref>Bell & Weinberg (1978): Tables 21.14 & 21.15, pages 453-454.</ref> and 1.5-2.5 times more likely for males.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Safren SA, Heimberg RG |title=Depression, hopelessness, suicidality, and related factors in sexual minority and heterosexual adolescents |journal=Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=859–66 |date=December 1999 |pmid=10596508 |doi=10.1037/0022-006X.67.6.859}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Russell ST, Joyner K |title=Adolescent Sexual Orientation and Suicide Risk: Evidence From a National Study |journal=American Journal of Public Health |volume=91 |issue=8 |pages=1276–81 |date=August 2001 |pmid=11499118 |pmc=1446760 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.91.8.1276}}</ref> The highs reach 4.6 more likely in females<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Saghir MT, Robins E, Walbran B, Gentry KA |title=Homosexuality. IV. Psychiatric disorders and disability in the female homosexual |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=127 |issue=2 |pages=147–54 |date=August 1970 |pmid=5473144 |url=http://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=5473144|doi=10.1176/ajp.127.2.147 }}</ref> and 14.6 more likely in males.<ref name="intro">ed. Sandfort, T; et al.  Lesbian and Gay Studies: An Introductory, Interdisciplinary Approach.  Chapter 2.</ref>

Race and age play a factor in the increased risk. The highest ratios for males are attributed to caucasians when they are in their youth. By the age of 25, their risk is down to less than half of what it was however black gay males risk steadily increases to 8.6 times more likely. Through a lifetime the risks are 5.7 for white and 12.8 for black gay and bisexual males.<ref name="intro"/>

Lesbian and bisexual females have opposite effects with less attempts in youth when compared to heterosexual females. Through a lifetime the likelihood to attempt nearly triple the youth 1.1 ratio for caucasian females, however for black females the rate is affected very little (less than 0.1 to 0.3 difference) with heterosexual black females having a slightly higher risk throughout most of the age-based study.<ref name="intro"/>

Gay and lesbian youth who attempt suicide are disproportionately subject to anti-gay attitudes, and have weaker skills for coping with discrimination, isolation, and loneliness,<ref name="intro"/><ref>Rotheram-Boris, et al. (1994); Proctor and Groze (1994)</ref> and were more likely to experience family rejection<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ryan C, Huebner D, Diaz RM, Sanchez J |title=Family rejection as a predictor of negative health outcomes in white and Latino lesbian, gay, and bisexual young adults |journal=Pediatrics |volume=123 |issue=1 |pages=346–52 |date=January 2009 |pmid=19117902 |doi=10.1542/peds.2007-3524}}</ref> than those who do not attempt suicide.  Another study found that gay and bisexual youth who attempted suicide had more feminine gender roles,<ref name=pmid2034492>{{cite journal |vauthors=Remafedi G, Farrow JA, Deisher RW |title=Risk factors for attempted suicide in gay and bisexual youth |journal=Pediatrics |volume=87 |issue=6 |pages=869–75 |date=June 1991 |pmid=2034492 |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/87/6/869}}</ref> adopted an LGB identity at a young age and were more likely than peers to report sexual abuse, drug abuse, and arrests for misconduct.<ref name=pmid2034492/>

One study found that same-sex sexual behavior, but not homosexual attraction or homosexual identity, was significantly predictive of suicide among Norwegian adolescents.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wichstrøm L, Hegna K |title=Sexual orientation and suicide attempt: a longitudinal study of the general Norwegian adolescent population |journal=Journal of Abnormal Psychology |volume=112 |issue=1 |pages=144–51 |date=February 2003 |pmid=12653422 |doi=10.1037/0021-843X.112.1.144}}</ref> In Denmark, the age-adjusted suicide mortality risk for men in registered domestic partnerships was nearly eight times greater than for men with positive histories of heterosexual marriage and nearly twice as high for men who had never married.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Mathy RM, Cochran SD, Olsen J, Mays VM |title=The association between relationship markers of sexual orientation and suicide: Denmark, 1990–2001 |journal=Soc Psychiatry Psychiatr Epidemiol |volume= 46|issue= 2|pages= 111–7|date=December 2009 |pmid=20033129 |doi=10.1007/s00127-009-0177-3 |pmc=3034881}}</ref>

A study of suicide, undertaken in Sweden, involved the analysis of data records for 6,456 [[Same-sex marriage|same-sex married]] couples and 1,181,723 man-women marriages.  Even with [[LGBT rights in Sweden|Sweden's tolerant attitude regarding homosexuality]], it was determined that for same-sex married men the suicide risk was nearly three times higher than for different-sex married men, even after an adjustment for HIV status.  For women, it was shown that there was a tentatively elevated suicide risk for same-sex married women over that of different-sex married women.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10654-016-0154-6  |title=Suicide in married couples in Sweden: Is the risk greater in same-sex couples |author=Björkenstam, Charlotte et al|date=11 May 2016|work=[[European Journal of Epidemiology]]|doi=10.1007/s10654-016-0154-6 | accessdate=27 November 2016 |volume=31 |pages=685–690}}</ref>

===Social factors===
Higher levels of social and national cohesion reduce suicide rates. Suicide levels are highest among the retired, [[unemployment|unemployed]], [[Poverty|impoverished]], [[divorce]]d, the childless, urbanites,{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} [[empty nester]]s, and other people who live alone. Suicide rates also rise during times of economic uncertainty. (Although [[poverty]] is not a direct cause, it can contribute to the risk of suicide).<ref name="Diego De Leo & Russell Evans Griffith University 2003">{{cite web
 | author=Diego De Leo & Russell Evans (Griffith University)
 | title=International Suicide Rates: Recent Trends and Implications for Australia
 | format=PDF
 | publisher=Australian Institute for Suicide Research and Prevention
 | year=2003
 | url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/1D2B4E895BCD429ECA2572290027094D/$File/intsui.pdf
 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824231716/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/1D2B4E895BCD429ECA2572290027094D/$File/intsui.pdf
 | archivedate=24 August 2012
 | accessdate=2008-08-29
}}</ref>

[[File:Suicides by month and day in the US, 1999-2004.png|thumb|left|Suicides by month and day of week for the United States, 1999–2004. Data from the CDC.<ref name="cdc.gov"/>]]
[[Epidemiology|Epidemiological]] studies generally show a relationship between suicide or suicidal behaviors and socio-economic disadvantage, including limited educational achievement, [[homelessness]], unemployment, economic dependence, and contact with the [[police]] or justice system.<ref name="Diego De Leo & Russell Evans Griffith University 2003"/> [[War]] is traditionally believed to be associated with a fall in suicide rates; however, this has been questioned in recent studies, showing a more complex picture than previously conceived.<ref>Changes in Scottish suicide rates during the Second World War. Rob Henderson, Cameron Stark, Roger W Humphry, Sivasubramaniam Selvaraj; BMC Public Health 2006, 6:167 {{doi|10.1186/1471-2458-6-167}}. http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2458/6/167</ref><ref>Suicide and the war in Croatia. A. Bosnar, V. Stemberga, M. Coklo, G. Zamolo Koncar, M. Definis-Gojanovic, V. Sendula-Jengic, P. Katic; Forensic Science Int, Volume 147, Supplement, Pages S13-S16 (17 January 2005), {{doi|10.1016/j.forsciint.2004.09.086}}. http://www.fsijournal.org/article/S0379-0738(04)00600-0/abstract</ref>

A 2015 UK study by the [[Office for National Statistics]], commissioned by [[Public Health England]], which considered 18,998 deaths of people aged between 20 and 64, found that men working in the construction industry and women employed in culture, media and sport, healthcare and primary school teaching were at the highest risk of suicide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/mar/17/male-construction-workers-greatest-risk-suicide-england-study-finds|title=Male construction workers at greatest risk of suicide, study finds|first=Haroon|last=Siddique|date=17 March 2017|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017|via=The Guardian}}</ref>

===Health and suicide===
[[File:Relationship between bmi and suicide.png|thumb|Risk of suicide decreases with increased body mass index in the United States.<ref name="pmid19907331">{{cite journal |vauthors=Mukamal KJ, Rimm EB, Kawachi I, O'Reilly EJ, Calle EE, Miller M |title=Body Mass Index and Risk of Suicide Among One Million US Adults |journal=Epidemiology |volume= 21|issue= 1|pages= 82–6|date=November 2009 |pmid=19907331 |doi=10.1097/EDE.0b013e3181c1fa2d |url=}}</ref>]]

[[Major depressive disorder|Depression]], either unipolar or as part of [[bipolar disorder]], is an especially common cause. [[Substance abuse]], severe physical disease or infirmity are also recognized causes.

An unknown number of suicidal fatalities are falsely presumed to be the consequences of severe illnesses, infectious, malignant, mental et cetera.{{clarify|date=August 2016}}

====Suicide and body mass index====
Risk of suicide may decrease with increased weight and is low in [[obesity|obese persons]].<ref name="pmid19907331" /> The connection is not well understood, but it is hypothesized that elevated body weight results in higher circulating levels of [[tryptophan]], [[serotonin]], and [[leptin]], which in turn reduces [[impulsivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ottar Bjerkeset |author2=Pål Romundstad |author3=Jonathan Evans |author4=David Gunnell |title=Association of Adult Body Mass Index and Height with Anxiety, Depression, and Suicide in the General Population|journal=Am. J. Epidemiol.|year=2008|url=http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/content/167/2/193.full|pmid=17981889|doi=10.1093/aje/kwm280|volume=167|issue=2|pages=193–202}}</ref>

However, other studies indicate that suicide rates increase with extreme obesity, and it is difficult to control for conflating factors such as BMI-related differences in longevity, which have a significant bearing on suicide rates.<ref name="Depression and anxiety">{{Cite journal|last=Wagner|first=B|title=Extreme obesity is associated with suicidal behavior and suicide attempts in adults: results of a population-based representative sample|work=Depression and Anxiety|publisher=Wiley Periodicals, Inc.|pmid=23576272|doi=10.1002/da.22105|volume=30|pages=975–81}}</ref>

===Seasonal suicide===
{{main|Seasonal effects on suicide rates}}
The idea that suicide is more common during the winter holidays (including [[Christmas]] in the [[northern hemisphere]]) is actually a myth, generally reinforced by media coverage associating suicide with the holiday season. The [[National Center for Health Statistics]] found that suicides drop during the winter months, and peak during spring and early summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17344747|title=Study: Suicides Drop During Holidays|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ViolencePrevention/suicide/holiday.html|title=Holiday Suicides: Fact or Myth-Suicide-Violence Prevention-Injury Center-CDC|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>  Considering that there is a correlation between the winter season and rates of depression,<ref>See [[Seasonal affective disorder]]</ref> there are theories that this might be accounted for by capability to commit suicide and relative cheerfulness.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/2013085-overview|title=Suicide: Practice Essentials, Overview, Etiology|date=28 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017|via=eMedicine}}</ref> Suicide has also been linked to other seasonal factors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/820241.stm|title=BBC News - HEALTH - Suicide 'linked to' the moon|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>

The variation in suicides by day of week is actually greater than any seasonal variation.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31780455/ns/health-mental_health/t/deadliest-day-suicides-wednesday/] NBC News article referencing a study published in Social Psychiatry and Psychiatric Epidemiology</ref>

===Suicide trends===
Certain time trends can be related to the type of death. In the [[United Kingdom]], for example, the steady rise in suicides from 1945 to 1962-63 was probably to some extent curtailed following the removal of [[carbon monoxide]] from domestic gas supplies which occurred with the change from [[coal gas]] to [[natural gas]] during the sixties.<ref>{{Cite journal | jstor = 25565893 | last1 = Kreitman | first1 = N. | title = The coal gas story. United Kingdom suicide rates, 1960-71 | journal = British Journal of Preventive and Social Medicine | volume = 30 | issue = 2 | pages = 86–93 | year = 1976 | pmid = 953381 | pmc = 478945 | doi=10.1136/jech.30.2.86}}</ref> Methods vary across cultures, and the easy availability of lethal agents and materials plays a role.

It is estimated that global annual suicide fatalities could rise to 1.5 million by 2020.
Worldwide, suicide ranks among the three leading causes of death among those aged 15–44 years. Suicide attempts are up to 20 times more frequent than completed suicides.<ref>{{cite web
 | author=Staff | title=SUPRE
 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]]
 | date=February 16, 2006
 | work=WHO sites: Mental Health
 | url=http://www.who.int/mental_health/prevention/suicide/supresuicideprevent/en/index.html
 | accessdate=2006-04-11
}}</ref>

===Historical trends===

Historical data show lower suicide rates during periods of war.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://academic.oup.com/ije/article/39/6/1464/736597/Suicide-in-England-and-Wales-1861-2007-a-time|title=Suicide in England and Wales 1861–2007: a time-trends analysis|first1=Kyla|last1=Thomas|first2=David|last2=Gunnell|date=1 December 2010|publisher=|journal=Int J Epidemiol|volume=39|issue=6|pages=1464–1475|accessdate=19 March 2017|via=ije.oxfordjournals.org|doi=10.1093/ije/dyq094}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/2263690.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Health - More suicides under Conservative rule|publisher=|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.ww2talk.com/index.php?threads/suicide.4779/</ref>

