{{Infobox person | name =James Wasserman | image =Jim-Wasserman-SMW.jpg | caption = | image_size = | birth_date = 1948 | birth_place = [[New Jersey]], United States | death_date = | death_place = }}
'''James Wasserman''' (born 1948)<ref>{{Cite web |title=James Wasserman Biography |accessdate=2011-07-19 |url=http://jameswassermanbooks.com/Jimbio.html |work=Jameswassermanbooks.com |publisher=James Wasserman Books}}</ref> is an American author and occultist. A member of [[Ordo Templi Orientis]] since 1976 and a book designer by trade, he has written extensively on spiritual and political liberty.
==Publishing career== Wasserman began working in 1973 at [[Weiser Books]], then the world’s largest bookstore and publishing company to specialize in esoteric literature. While working at Weiser, he met and befriended legendary filmmakers and occultists [[Harry Everett Smith|Harry Smith]] and [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Igliori |first=Paola |title=American Magus: Harry Smith |page=275 |publisher=Inandout Press |location=New York, NY |year=1996 |isbn=0-9625119-9-4}}</ref> Wasserman worked with Brazilian occultist [[Marcelo Ramos Motta]] to publish the ''Commentaries of AL'' in 1975, for which he wrote the introduction. Additionally, he supervised the 1976 Weiser publication of [[The Book of the Law]], the first popular edition to append the holograph manuscript to the typeset text.<ref>{{cite book |last=Crowley |first=Aleister |authorlink=Aleister Crowley |title=The Book of the Law |publisher=Samuel Weiser |location=New York, NY |year=1976 |isbn=0-87728-334-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James |title=In the Center of the Fire: A Memoir of the Occult 1966-1989 |page=111 |publisher=Ibis Press |location=Lake Worth, FL |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-89254-201-7}}</ref> In 1977, Wasserman arranged to professionally re-photograph [[Frieda Harris]]' [[Tarot]] paintings for use in an improved second edition of [[Aleister Crowley]]'s [[Thoth tarot deck|Thoth Tarot]] deck, and also wrote the instruction booklet.<ref name="Just Energy Radio">{{cite web|last=Louise |first=Rita |url=http://www.justenergyradio.com/archive-pages/jwasserman.htm |title=James Wasserman - Secrets of Masonic Washington |work=Justenergyradio.com |publisher=Body, Mind & SoulHealer |accessdate=November 22, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203104002/http://www.justenergyradio.com/archive-pages/jwasserman.htm |archivedate=December 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
Wasserman left Weiser in 1977 to found Studio 31, where he produced the ''[[Simon Necronomicon]]'', a volume purporting to be the mythological ''[[Necronomicon]]'' made famous by [[Howard Philips Lovecraft]].<ref>{{cite book |editor=Simon |title=The Necronomicon |publisher=Schlangekraft/Barnes Graphic |location=New York, NY |year=1977}}</ref> In 2008, it was reissued in a high-quality 31st anniversary edition by Ibis Press. In 1994, Wasserman assembled a team of scholars, photographers, and editorial staff to produce a full-color version of ''The Egyptian Book of the Dead'' featuring the [[Papyrus of Ani]] as discussed in [[In the Center of the Fire]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James |title=In the Center of the Fire: A Memoir of the Occult 1966-1989 |pages=145–147 |publisher=Ibis Press |location=Lake Worth, FL |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-89254-201-7}}</ref> His edition of the Book of the Dead was described as offering "much of value in presentation, layout and commentary"<ref>{{Cite news | last = Baines | first = John | title = The Egyptian Book of the Dead | work = Times Higher Education | location = London | accessdate = 2011-07-19 | date = 1995-04-21 | url = http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=161790&sectioncode=41 }}</ref> by [[John Baines (Egyptologist)|John Baines]], professor of [[Egyptology]] at the [[University of Oxford]]. In 2014, the Twentieth Anniversary Edition was completed, revised and expanded, adding: "Thoughts on this Twentieth Anniversary Edition" by James Wasserman; "Coming Forth Into the Day" by [[J. Daniel Gunther]]; and "An Annotated Bibliography and Study Guide" by Dr. Ogden Goelet. This new edition includes some corrections and improvements to the color plates, and was completely recreated in electronic format.
==Ordo Templi Orientis== A member of O.T.O. since 1976, Wasserman founded one of its oldest lodges, Tahuti Lodge, in [[New York City]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tahutilodge.org/history.php |title=Tahuti Lodge O.T.O., serving the New York City Metropolitan Area |year=2009 |work=Tahutilodge.org |publisher=Tahuti Lodge, [[Ordo Templi Orientis]] |accessdate=November 22, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123143703/http://tahutilodge.org/history.php |archivedate=November 23, 2011 |df= }}</ref> He has played a key role within the Order in publishing the literary corpus of Aleister Crowley. In 1983, he worked with two other members of O.T.O. to produce ''[[The Holy Books of Thelema]],''<ref name="Just Energy Radio"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Crowley |first=Aleister |authorlink=Aleister Crowley |title=The Holy Books of Thelema |publisher=Samuel Weiser |location=York Beach, Maine |year=1983 |isbn=0-87728-579-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James |title=In the Center of the Fire: A Memoir of the Occult 1966-1989 |page=187 |publisher=Ibis Press |location=Lake Worth, FL |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-89254-201-7}}</ref> a collection of Crowley’s Class A (inspired) writings. In 1986, his essay “An Introduction to the History of the O.T.O.” appeared in ''[[The Equinox]] III, No. 10''. In 2009, he and his wife Nancy published ''To Perfect This Feast,''<ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James & Nancy|title=To Perfect This Feast: A Commentary on Liber XV |page=3 |publisher=Sekmet Books |year=2010|edition =2nd |isbn=978-0-9718870-3-9}}</ref> a performance commentary on the [[Liber XV, The Gnostic Mass|Gnostic Mass]]. Revised for a second edition in 2010, the book is now in its third and final edition, published 2013. Wasserman is described by Dan Burstein as "a founder of the modern Ordo Templi Orientis” in his guide to [[Dan Brown]]'s novel ''Angels & Demons''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Burstein |first=Dan |title=Secrets of Angels and Demons |page=140 |publisher=CDS Books |location=New York, NY |year=2004 |isbn=1-59315-140-3}}</ref> In 2012, Wasserman wrote ''In the Center of the Fire'', an extensive account of his own experiences in the development of the modern O.T.O.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James |title=In the Center of the Fire: A Memoir of the Occult 1966-1989 |page=3 |publisher=Ibis Press |location=Lake Worth, FL |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-89254-201-7}}</ref> In 2015, he designed and produced a collection of essays for Ordo Templi Orientis published as ''Success Is Your Proof: One Hundred Years of O.T.O. in North America: A Festschrift in Honor of Hymenaeus Beta, Celebrating Thirty Years of Leadership''. He contributed an essay entitled "The New Aeon in the New World: The Law of Liberty in the Wild West." Eleven other ranking members of the Order contributed essays on a wide range of topics such as Thelemic doctrine, magical practices, Order history, and biographical treatments.
==Underlying philosophy== Wasserman’s work in O.T.O. and his numerous writings point to a philosophy based on individual liberty and the opportunity for direct personal experience of God within.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James|title=Divine Warriors: The Birth of Heresy |page=84 |publisher=Destiny Books |year=2017}}</ref> This more modern conception of [[Gnosticism]] dispenses with the myriad variations of the term as it is applied to numerous sub sects within major religions long ago. Modern Gnosticism simply presupposes the ability to forge a direct link with the highest level of divinity.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wasserman |first=James |title=The Temple of Solomon: From Ancient Israel to Secret Societies |page=18 |publisher=Inner Traditions |location=Rochester, VT |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-59477-220-7}}</ref> Wasserman further advances the notion that political liberty offers humanity the best conditions for spiritual growth.<ref>[http://jameswassermanbooks.com/Political-liberty.html Political Liberty as a Spiritual Value]</ref>
==Public appearances== Wasserman has appeared on several television networks including The History Channel, The Discovery Channel, National Geographic TV; and numerous radio broadcasts including NPR, Coast to Coast Radio, and 21st Century Radio.<ref>[http://jameswassermanbooks.com/jim-mediapage.html James Wasserman Media Page]</ref> In 2009, he discussed his book ''Secrets of Masonic Washington'' at the National Press Club in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{YouTube |id=0QDMK_CUeP8 |title=James Wasserman at the National Press Club 2009 Part 1}}</ref> In 2012, his performance of Liber Israfel was broadcast on The Discovery Channel in a program entitled Secrets of Secret Societies. In 2013, Swirling Star Lodge filmed a 50-minute talk he presented on a modern history of the O.T.O, a supplement to ''In the Center of the Fire''.<ref>{{YouTube |id=TmDsxyTc3a8 |title=James Wasserman at Swirling Star Lodge, "A Modern History of the O.T.O." 2013 }}</ref> In 2014, Swirling Star Lodge released a video of a performance of the Gnostic Mass based on the instructions in ''To Perfect This Feast'' <ref>{{YouTube |id=VhUpJubHlAc |title=To Perfect This Feast: The Gnostic Mass 2014 }}</ref> In May 2015, Wasserman addressed the O.T.O. in Vancouver, British Columbia in celebration of its one hundredth year in North America. In 2017 he addressed NOTOCON on "The Roots of O.T.O. in the Crusades," a public version of which is on his website.
