{{DEFAULTSORT:Boljevic, Ruvim}} [[Category:17th-century Serbian people]] [[Category:17th-century Eastern Orthodox bishops]] [[Category:Serbian Orthodox metropolitans of Montenegro]] [[Category:People from Bar, Montenegro]] [[Category:1685 deaths]] [[Category:Date of birth unknown]]

The '''Samaritan's dilemma''' is a dilemma in the act of [[charity (practice)|charity]]. It hinges on the idea that when presented with charity, in some location such as a [[soup kitchen]], a person will act in one of two ways: using the charity to improve their situation, or coming to rely on charity as a means of survival. The term ''Samaritan's dilemma'' was coined by economist [[James M. Buchanan]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YwoWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Samaritan%27s+dilemma%22&dq=%22Samaritan%27s+dilemma%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=BqiUT5rlN6jG6AHFi_GPBA&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBg Roger E. Meiners, "Victim Compensation", Lexington Books, 1978 p. 99]</ref>
The argument against charity frequently cites the Samaritan's dilemma as reason to forgo charitable contributions. It is also a common argument against [[communism]] and [[socialism]], claiming that state [[aid]] is equivalent to charity, and that the beneficiaries of such aid will become [[Sloth (deadly sin)|slothful]] or otherwise negligent members of [[society]]. The more aid that is received the less likely the recipient will seek out a permanent solution for their condition. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fee.org/articles/the-samaritans-dilemma-and-the-welfare-state/|title=The Samaritans Dilemma and the Welfare State {{!}} E.C. Pasour|date=1991-06-01|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en-US}}</ref>
The dilemma's name is a reference to the biblical [[Parable of the Good Samaritan]].
== Samaritan's dilemma in disaster preparedness == A study published in 2016 looked at 5089 major [[Natural disaster|natural disasters]] in 81 [[Developing country|developing countries]] over a 33 year period. Results showed that among the countries that received natural disaster relief had less incentives to provide their own natural disaster protections. This effect is exacerbated the poorer and less-developed the country is that receives the aid.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Raschky|first=Paul A.|last2=Schwindt|first2=Manijeh|title=Aid, Catastrophes and the Samaritan's Dilemma|url=https://doi-org.ezproxy.uky.edu/10.1111/ecca.12194|journal=Economica|volume=83|issue=332|pages=624–645|doi=10.1111/ecca.12194}}</ref>
== Avoiding the Samaritan's dilemma == Much foreign aid comes in the form of monetary compensation for damages or direct relief such as food or water. This type of direct aid does not provide any incentive for the recipient to become independent. By introducing incentives that developing countries can meet by building up natural disaster protection the effects of the Samaritan's dilemma can be effectively mitigated.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/60856158|title=The samaritan's dilemma : the political economy of development aid|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Gibson, Clark C., 1961-|isbn=9780199278848|location=Oxford|oclc=60856158}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Criticisms of welfare]] *[[Aid]] *[[Moral hazard]]
