'''Whegs''' (''wheel-legs or wing-legs'') are mechanisms for [[robot]] locomotion. Whegs use a strategy of locomotion that combines the simplicity of the [[wheel]] with the obstacle-clearing advantages of the foot.
Whegs were pioneered at the Biologically Inspired Robotics Laboratory at [[Case Western Reserve University]]. Whegs development and improvements based on [[cockroach]] climbing behavior in several robots has been done in collaboration with the Ritzmann lab in the Biology department at [[Case Western Reserve University]] on cockroach climbing behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biorobots.case.edu/projects/whegs/whegs-i/|title=Whegs™ I {{!}} Biologically Inspired Robotics|website=biorobots.case.edu|access-date=2016-09-21}}</ref>
Whegs robots were inspired by the Prolero robot, designed in 1996 at [[European Space Agency|the European Space Agency]], and the [[rhex|RHex]] robot, developed by a multiuniversity effort funded by the [[Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency]].<ref>[http://biorobots.cwru.edu/projects/whegs/ Whegs Series Robots]</ref> The mobility system is based on studies on the locomotion of the cockroach.<ref>{{cite paper | title = Comparing Cockroach and Whegs Robot Body Motions | citeseerx = 10.1.1.84.5410 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/288/5463/80.summary|last=Taubes|first=Gary|year=2000|title=Biologists and Engineers Create a New Generation of Robots That Imitate Life|journal=Science|volume=288|issue=5463|pages=80–83|doi=10.1126/science.288.5463.80|accessdate=November 2011}}{{subscription required}}</ref>
Wing-legs are found on flying robots and are [[Wing|wings]] dual-purposed as legs for locomotion when the robot is on the ground.<ref>Laboratory of Intelligent Systems [http://lis.epfl.ch/DALER DALER project]</ref>
